Posted: Fri Apr 06, 2012 8:59 am
ronelson wrote:Quote:I think it all fairness, for these guys it's a job. Guys that win a lot get paid and guys that lose a lot get fired. Holding winning above all other considerations probably isn't ethical, but the fact that it happens isn't exactly surprising.There's a difference between, "Let's go out and kick their asses!" and, "Let's go out and put them all on injured reserve!" I say this as someone who defended them before because I didn't think a bounty program on its face necessarily implied much of a difference in how they played the game. But telling your guys to take cheap shots in the pile before the refs pull you off? To me, it's not even about the bounty program anymore, it's about a guy who was maliciously trying to harm people, and being in a position where he was able to coerce others into doing it.I don't know. The reaction I mostly heard from ex-pro and ex-big-time-college players was pretty much a resounding shrug. The general consensus was that coaches were always aware of injuries on the other side and exploiting those injuries definitely came up in meetings. The Herm quote has become a joke, but you do play to win the game. At the pro level, winning is incentivized far, far above any other concern.I'm not saying it's right - but the faux-outrage and disbelief that something like this could possibly be going on is ridiculous. It's a violent game. Hitting the other guy so hard that he can't go on or at least is thinking more about protecting himself than the play has been part of the game for a long time, for better or worse. Literally everyone that's old enough to play even junior high football was alive when the biggest defensive highlight show on TV was called "Jacked Up".It's cynical, I admit, but the big public crackdown seems like PR spin. The NFL ignored concussion studies until it couldn't anymore, and now they're "fixing" it. It's extremely important that the NFL convinces the general public that dirty players who flaunt the new rules and deliver excessive hits are what makes football dangerous. That's something they can sort of police. If the conversation turns to the actual science and the fact that repeated, sub-concussive blows to the head can cause serious damage, the NFL is in a much more uncomfortable position.
