RDeVoe wrote:Quote:It's cynical, I admit, but the big public crackdown seems like PR spin. The NFL ignored concussion studies until it couldn't anymore, and now they're "fixing" it. It's extremely important that the NFL convinces the general public that dirty players who flaunt the new rules and deliver excessive hits are what makes football dangerous. That's something they can sort of police. If the conversation turns to the actual science and the fact that repeated, sub-concussive blows to the head can cause serious damage, the NFL is in a much more uncomfortable position. I don't think so. I mean everybody knows how baddly boxing messed up Mohamed Ali and nobody cares. I really think you are overestimating peoples concern about pro-players.If no one cares, why bother with any of it? The big collisions with helmets colliding aren't all that meaningful in the grand scheme of things. It's not like Ali took a handful of really big punches and barring those he'd be perfectly fine. All evidence indicates that the cumulative effect of repeated, small blows to the head is bad for your brain. The NFL can't really fix that any more than boxing can, yet they're taking a big showy stand on protect players' heads. Why, if not for PR purposes?
