Posted: Fri Apr 06, 2012 3:03 pm
RyricKrael wrote:They are focusing on limiting the major hits that can destroy a players career with one hit. They are removing plays that have little to no effect on the game except to injure another player. They are taking steps to ensure player saftey while not throwing out the entire sport. How is that difficult to understand? Of course it is PR, big hits that end a career is what gets media attention, repeated hits for 8 years of HS/College ball and then professional career don't.But the entire sport isn't safe. That's sort of my point. Arguably, a bit hit the ends a guy's career is better for his long term health. If playing football is fundamentally bad for your brain, the sooner your career ends the better off you'll be. I absolutely agree that they can't change that without fundamentally altering the game. I completely get why they don't want to turn the NFL into flag football. But refusing to make drastic changes does mean player safety is not the top priority.
