As kind of an aside, I used to work with (and am still distant friends with) a scientist who works almost solely on testing and improving PPE (personal protective equipment) including sports gear. He devised quite a few tests for helmets that apparently are now becoming standardized and required for any new products that get approved by NCAA/NFL type associations. Really smart guy. I haven't talked to him in several years, but I did see him on TV once, talking about the direct improvements that Riddell made in direct response to some of his testing and monitoring methodologies. Cool part was, when we used to work together, part of his lab was a deep freezer filled with cadaver parts...including human heads.
