ronelson
Ars Legatus Legionis
Tribus: Richmond, VA
Registered: Mar 21, 1999Posts: 21393
Posted: Sat Apr 07, 2012 5:20 am
Quote:Because they would have to start using flags if small blows to the head were going to be considered.In flag football, you don't get a helmet and you still take blows to the head. It wouldn't address the issue and arguably would make it worse.The reason concussions are talked about is because they are a noticeable and measurable injury with serious side effects, many in the very short term and some in the short term. Once someone has one, their brain has a high likelyhood of swelling. A second concussion in the same game can kill that person. Small hits may cause negative side effects later in life or they may not, but they frequently do not cause A) brain swelling, B) increased risk of death within 24 hours, C) increased risk of seizures within 24 hours (see Chargers), D) loss of balance and cognizance that can lead to further serious injuries, head-related or otherwise, or E) continued concussion-related symptoms for weeks or months (see Sydney Crosby, Rodgers, Roethlisberger).Quote:The general consensus was that coaches were always aware of injuries on the other side and exploiting those injuries definitely came up in meetings.This I agree with. If a guy does anything from tweak his ankle to get a concussion, you test him. But you don't intentionally try to break his neck or ankles or eye-gouge him in the piles. If for some reason you do think actions that are prohibited by the rules are okay, you shouldn't be surprised when there are consequences for getting caught.Quote:Cool part was, when we used to work together, part of his lab was a deep freezer filled with cadaver parts...including human heads.My wife works in the anatomy and biology department at a college. They were renovating her new lab space when she started and she found a human skull in a jar. She told the department head, who shook his head and muttered, "Again?" Pysgard
